<dl id="n26262h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26262h">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26262h"> 262(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> execration <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n26262h"><li>FW 35.20 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n26262h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n26262h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n26262h">MS BL 47475-105v</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:120 <a name="bd8y" href="../../ff/fdra/bda.htm#bd8y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/bd8.htm#n26262h">Draft: I.2&sect;1.8</a>+/2.8+/3.8+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The XII. Tables]</font>&mdash;In form the laws contained in the Tables were of remarkable brevity, terseness and pregnancy, with something of a rhythmical cadence that must have greatly facilitated their retention in the memory. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The system as a whole is one of <i>jus</i> as distinguished from <i>fas</i>. In the royal laws <mark>execration</mark> (<i>sacratio capitis</i>, <i>sacer esto</i>) was a common sanction; but in the Tables it occurs only once pure and simple, and that with reference to an offence that could be committed only by a patrician,&mdash;material loss caused by a patron to his client <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Hanging and beheading, flogging to death, burning at the stake, throwing from the Tarpeian rock,&mdash;such are secular penalties that are met in the Tables <small> &ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo; <a name="EBRL2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL2"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 538</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
